==History==
===Early career and ''I Brought You My Bullets, You Brought Me Your Love'' (2001–2002)===
{{Main|I Brought You My Bullets, You Brought Me Your Love}}
[[File:WTC smoking on 9-11.jpeg|thumb|Witnessing the [[September 11 attacks]] influenced Way to form My Chemical Romance.]]
The band was formed by frontman [[Gerard Way]] and drummer Matt Pelissier in [[Newark, New Jersey]], soon after the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name="allmusic">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/my-chemical-romance-mn0000520545|title=My Chemical Romance|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=April 21, 2020|archive-date=March 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302144145/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/my-chemical-romance-mn0000520545|url-status=live}}</ref> Witnessing the [[World Trade Center (1973–2001)|World Trade Center]] towers fall influenced Way's life to the extent that he decided to start a band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wow.cl/prontus_wow/site/artic/20080223/pags/20080223211406.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080313074511/http://www.wow.cl/prontus_wow/site/artic/20080223/pags/20080223211406.html|title=Press conference held in Chile|date=February 2008|access-date=December 18, 2013|archive-date=March 13, 2008}}</ref> Way has said "music was this thing I secretly wanted to do"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xrCUEY8rgPE|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119101211/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xrCUEY8rgPE|archive-date=January 19, 2021|title=My Chemical Romance: Question and Answer Interview|website=[[YouTube]]|access-date=December 4, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and later wrote the song "Skylines and Turnstiles" to express his feelings about September 11 and shortly thereafter, [[Ray Toro]] was recruited as the band's guitarist because at the time Way could not sing and play the [[guitar]] simultaneously.<ref name="alt press">{{cite web|url=http://www.theimmortalityproject.com/fansite/press/apnov04.html |title=Art Imitates Life – My Chemical Romance |access-date=2006-12-23 |publisher=Alternative Press |year=2004 |author=Simon, Leslie |work=Alternative Press Magazine |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128135648/http://www.theimmortalityproject.com/fansite/press/apnov04.html |archive-date=November 28, 2006 }}</ref>

The name of the band was suggested by bass guitarist [[Mikey Way]], younger brother of Gerard, who was working in a [[Barnes & Noble]] when he was struck by the title of a book by [[Irvine Welsh]] named ''[[Ecstasy: Three Tales of Chemical Romance]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kerrang.com/8181/11-things-didnt-know-chemical-romance/|title=11 Things You Didn't know about My Chemical Romance|work=Kerrang!|access-date=March 7, 2016|archive-date=March 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305162551/http://www.kerrang.com/8181/11-things-didnt-know-chemical-romance/|url-status=live}}</ref> The first recording sessions were undertaken in Pelissier's attic, where the songs "Our Lady of Sorrows" and "Cubicles" were recorded. The band refers to those sessions as "The Attic Demos".<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Whitt|first1=Cassie|title=My Chemical Romance to release "Attic Demos," more unheard material with greatest hits compilation|url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/my_chemical_romance_to_release_attic_demos_new_materials_with_greatest_hits|magazine=Alternative Press|access-date=January 12, 2016|archive-date=January 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127153609/http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/my_chemical_romance_to_release_attic_demos_new_materials_with_greatest_hits|url-status=live}}</ref> After hearing the demo and dropping out of college, Mikey Way decided to join the band. While with [[Eyeball Records]], the band met [[Frank Iero]], the lead vocalist and guitarist for [[Pencey Prep]]. Following Pencey Prep's split in 2002, Iero became a member of My Chemical Romance, just days prior to the recording of the band's debut album.<ref name="alt press"/> They recorded their debut album, ''[[I Brought You My Bullets, You Brought Me Your Love]]'', just three months after the formation of the band and released it in 2002 through Eyeball Records.<ref name="allmusic"/> The album was produced by [[Thursday (band)|Thursday]] frontman [[Geoff Rickley]] after the band became friends with him while playing shows in New Jersey.<ref>{{cite web|first=Alex|last=Henderson|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/i-brought-you-my-bullets-you-brought-me-your-love-mw0000230089|title=My Chemical Romance I Brought You My Bullets, You Brought Me Your Love|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=July 24, 2018|archive-date=July 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725122847/https://www.allmusic.com/album/i-brought-you-my-bullets-you-brought-me-your-love-mw0000230089|url-status=live}}</ref> Iero played guitar on two of the tracks, one of which was "Early Sunsets Over Monroeville". During this time, the band was booked at the infamous venue Big Daddy's, where it began to receive more attention.<ref name=bucks>{{cite web| last = Cirone| first = Jason| title = MCR goes the way of the Beatles, Nirvana| publisher = The Courier-Tribune Asheboro North Carolina| date = March 13, 2013| url = http://courier-tribune.com/sections/get/hear/mcr-goes-way-beatles-nirvana.html| access-date = February 14, 2014| archive-date = February 22, 2014| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140222191825/http://courier-tribune.com/sections/get/hear/mcr-goes-way-beatles-nirvana.html| url-status = live}}</ref>

My Chemical Romance offered free downloads through [[PureVolume]] and the social networking website [[MySpace]], where they gained an initial fan base.<ref name="downloads">{{cite news | url= https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2005-03-09-internet-jukebox_x.htm | newspaper= [[USA Today]] | title= Music fans reach for the stars | first= Edna | last= Gundersen | date= March 9, 2005 | access-date= April 9, 2010 | archive-date= September 16, 2011 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110916212443/http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2005-03-09-internet-jukebox_x.htm | url-status= live }}</ref><ref name="wired">{{cite magazine | url= https://www.wired.com/news/culture/0,67545-0.html | magazine= [[Wired (magazine)|Wired Magazine]] | title= Bands Embrace Social Networking | date= 2005-05-18 | access-date= March 10, 2017 | archive-date= July 6, 2008 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080706042426/http://www.wired.com/news/culture/0,67545-0.html | url-status= live }}</ref>

===Major label signing and ''Three Cheers for Sweet Revenge'' (2003–2006)===
{{Main|Three Cheers for Sweet Revenge}}
On August 31, 2003, the band announced via their website that they had signed a deal with [[Reprise Records]].<ref name="allmusic"/><ref>{{Cite web |last=Punknews.org |title=My Chemical Romance signs to Reprise |url=https://www.punknews.org/article/6973/my-chemical-romance-signs-to-reprise |access-date=2022-03-22 |website=www.punknews.org |language=en}}</ref> Following a tour with [[Avenged Sevenfold]], the band began working on their second album, which was titled ''[[Three Cheers for Sweet Revenge]]'', which was released on June 8, 2004. A month after the album's release, the band replaced Matt Pelissier with [[Bob Bryar]].<ref name="allmusic"/><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=My Chemical Romance|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/My-Chemical-Romance|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210308104150/https://www.britannica.com/topic/My-Chemical-Romance|archive-date=March 8, 2021|access-date=9 March 2021|website=Britannica|publisher=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> The band released four singles from the album: "[[I'm Not Okay (I Promise)]]", "[[Thank You for the Venom]]", "[[Helena (My Chemical Romance song)|Helena]]", and "[[The Ghost of You]]".<ref name=FMQB>{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16771 |title=FMQB Airplay Archive: Modern Rock |publisher=Friday Morning Quarterback Album Report, Incorporated |access-date=October 30, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130322142732/http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16771 |archive-date=March 22, 2013 }}</ref> The album went platinum in just over a year after its release.<ref name="bucks" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=My%20Chemical%20Romance&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2009&sort=Artist&perPage=25|title=My Chemical Romance on the RIAA|website=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924151606/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1|archive-date=2015-09-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Three Cheers RIAA database|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=Three%20Cheers&artist=My%20Chemical%20Romance&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=Platinum&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25|publisher=[[RIAA]]|access-date=November 5, 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924153434/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=Three%20Cheers&artist=My%20Chemical%20Romance&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=Platinum&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25|archive-date=September 24, 2015}}</ref>

At the beginning of 2005, the band was featured on the first [[Taste of Chaos]] tour along with [[The Used]] and [[Killswitch Engage]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/killswitch-engage-to-tour-with-the-used-my-chemical-romance/|title=Killswitch Engage To Tour With The Used, My Chemical Romance|work=Blabbermouth|date=November 18, 2004|access-date=July 24, 2018|archive-date=July 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725063519/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/killswitch-engage-to-tour-with-the-used-my-chemical-romance/|url-status=live}}</ref> The band also was the opening act for [[Green Day]] on their ''[[American Idiot]]'' tour.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rashbaum|first1=Alyssa|title=Idiots Hit The Road Again: Green Day Tour Dates Announced|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1496664/idiots-hit-the-road-again-green-day-tour-dates-announced/|website=MTV|date=February 8, 2005|access-date=November 18, 2016|archive-date=November 19, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119060651/http://www.mtv.com/news/1496664/idiots-hit-the-road-again-green-day-tour-dates-announced/|url-status=live}}</ref> They then co-headlined [[Warped Tour 2005]] with [[Fall Out Boy]] and co-headlined a tour with [[Alkaline Trio]] and [[Reggie and the Full Effect]] around the US.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rocksound.tv/features/read/warped-tour-2005-a-retrospective|title=Warped Tour 2005: A Retrospective|magazine=Rock Sound|date=July 3, 2018|access-date=July 24, 2018|archive-date=July 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725092618/https://www.rocksound.tv/features/read/warped-tour-2005-a-retrospective|url-status=live}}</ref> That same year, My Chemical Romance collaborated with [[The Used]] for a cover of the [[Queen (band)|Queen]] and [[David Bowie]] classic, "[[Under Pressure#My Chemical Romance and the Used version|Under Pressure]]", which was released as a benefit single for [[Music for Relief|tsunami relief]] on [[iTunes]] and other Internet outlets.<ref>{{cite web|first=James|last=Montgomeru|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1498187/my-chemical-romance-cover-under-pressure-plan-big-rock-lp/|title=My Chemical Romance Cover 'Under Pressure,' Plan 'Big Rock' LP|publisher=MTV|date=March 16, 2005|access-date=July 24, 2018|archive-date=July 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725063557/http://www.mtv.com/news/1498187/my-chemical-romance-cover-under-pressure-plan-big-rock-lp/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In March 2006, the album ''[[Life on the Murder Scene]]'' was released, incorporating a [[Compact Disc|CD]] and two [[DVD]]s. It included one documentary DVD chronicling the band's history, and a second DVD with music videos, the making of their videos and live performances. An [[unauthorized biography]] DVD ''Things That Make You Go MMM!'' was also released in June 2006. The DVD does not actually feature any My Chemical Romance music clips or performances but contains interviews with those who knew the band before much of their fame.<ref>{{cite web|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r801000|pure_url=yes}} |title=Allmusic review}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/life-on-the-murder-scene-20060309 |title=My Chemical Romance: Life On The Murder Scene |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=March 9, 2006 |access-date=November 16, 2017 |author=Eliscu, Jenny |archive-date=November 17, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117122922/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/life-on-the-murder-scene-20060309 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Things That Make You Go MMM Product info">{{cite web | url= http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=7100253 | publisher= cduniverse.com | title= Things That Make You Go MMM Product info | access-date= September 7, 2006 | archive-date= June 21, 2018 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180621043005/https://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=7100253 | url-status= live }}</ref> A biography titled ''Something Incredible This Way Comes'' was also released, written by [[Paul Stenning]] and published in 2006. It features information on their beginnings right through to their third album, ''The Black Parade''.

===''The Black Parade'' (2006–2009)===
{{Main|The Black Parade}}
[[File:Mcr hammersmith album announcement.jpg|thumb|Announcement of ''The Black Parade'' at London [[Hammersmith Palais]], 22 August 2006]]

My Chemical Romance started recording their third studio album on April 10, 2006 with [[Rob Cavallo]], producer of many of Green Day's albums.<ref name="pauseandplay">{{cite web | url=http://www.pauseandplay.com/upcoming.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060411213803/http://www.pauseandplay.com/upcoming.htm | archive-date=2006-04-11 | publisher= Pause & Play | title= Upcoming Albums}} Retrieved from Internet Archive February 15, 2014.</ref><ref name="punknews">{{cite web | url= http://www.punknews.org/article.php?sid=16269&mode=thread&order=0&thold=0 | publisher= Punknews.org | title= My Chemical Romance | url-status= dead | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070930192033/http://www.punknews.org/article.php?sid=16269&mode=thread&order=0&thold=0 | archive-date= September 30, 2007 }}</ref> It was originally thought to be titled ''The Rise and Fall of My Chemical Romance'' (in reference to ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]'' by [[David Bowie]]), but in an interview with ''[[Kerrang!]]'' magazine, Gerard Way suggested this was just the album's working title, stating "It was never the title of the album, more a spoof, or joke."<ref name="blackparade">{{cite web | url= http://www.theblackparade.com | publisher= Theblackparade.com | title= The Black Parade | url-status= dead | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20061017195024/http://www.theblackparade.com/ | archive-date= October 17, 2006 }}</ref>

On August 3, 2006, the band completed shooting the videos for their first two singles from the album, "[[Welcome to the Black Parade]]" and although not released until January 2007, "[[Famous Last Words (My Chemical Romance song)|Famous Last Words]]".<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.videostatic.com/content/new-release-my-chemical-romance-famous-last-words | title= NEW RELEASE: My Chemical Romance "Famous Last Words" | publisher= VideoStatic | date= January 18, 2007 | access-date= August 26, 2018 | archive-date= August 27, 2018 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180827142334/https://www.videostatic.com/content/new-release-my-chemical-romance-famous-last-words | url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.videostatic.com/content/mtv-adds-week-11507 | title= MTV Adds for the Week of 01/15/07 | publisher= VideoStatic | date= January 10, 2007 | access-date= August 26, 2018 | archive-date= August 27, 2018 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180827142340/https://www.videostatic.com/content/mtv-adds-week-11507 | url-status= live }}</ref> Both videos were directed by [[Samuel Bayer]], director of [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]'s "[[Smells Like Teen Spirit]]" and Green Day's ''[[American Idiot]]'' videos.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.videostatic.com/vs/2006/07/booked-my-chemical-romance-samuel-bayer-director.html | title= BOOKED: My Chemical Romance - Samuel Bayer, director | publisher= VideoStatic | date= July 26, 2006 | access-date= August 26, 2018 | archive-date= August 27, 2018 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180827142356/https://www.videostatic.com/vs/2006/07/booked-my-chemical-romance-samuel-bayer-director.html | url-status= live }}</ref> During filming for the second video, band members Gerard Way and Bob Bryar were injured. Way suffered torn ligaments in his ankle, and Bryar a burn to the leg which caused a severe [[staph infection]] that needed constant monitoring in the hospital. Consequently, the band was forced to cancel a few tour dates. While these injuries were reported by several news agencies to have been the result of a car accident, a statement released by the band on their website and [[MySpace]] page confirmed that these injuries occurred on the set of the video.<ref name="mychemicalromance">[http://www.mychemicalromance.com/flashsite.php]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060819035603/http://www.mychemicalromance.com/flashsite.php |date=August 19, 2006 }}</ref>[[File:My Chemical Romance BDO Feb 4 07 1.jpg|thumb|right|The band during the [[Big Day Out]] in February 2007]]On August 22, 2006, the band played a special one-off show at the 1,800-capacity London [[Hammersmith Palais]]. The show sold out in 15 minutes, which led to tickets being [[ticket resale|re-sold]] on [[eBay]] at prices well above face value. The name of the album was announced and 20 people dressed in black capes with their faces obscured paraded around the Hammersmith venue, followed by a large group of fans and street team members with signs saying "The Black Parade". Later during the show, the album title and the UK release date were confirmed. Before the band took the stage, it was announced that My Chemical Romance was unable to play, but they would be replaced by The Black Parade. After initial crowd hostility, it became clear the band was simply performing under a pseudonym in keeping with the theme of the album. Since then, the band would often perform under the alias "The Black Parade", wearing the costumes seen in the album's music videos. Gerard Way would adopt the persona of the leader of the [[marching band]], The Black Parade, and vary his behavior and performance accordingly.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/live/reviews-my-chemical-romance-8017|title=My Chemical Romance: Hammersmith Palais, London; Tuesday, August 22|magazine=NME|date=September 13, 2006|access-date=July 24, 2018|archive-date=July 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725063402/https://www.nme.com/reviews/live/reviews-my-chemical-romance-8017|url-status=live}}</ref> The band were [[Bottling (concert abuse)|bottled]] during a performance at the [[Reading and Leeds Festivals|Reading Festival]] by fans of the band [[Slayer]], who performed before them at the festival; Way later described it as their "greatest victory as a show".<ref name=":2" />

"[[Welcome to the Black Parade]]" was released as a single on September 11, 2006. On September 26, 2006, the music video for "Welcome to the Black Parade" was released in the UK, and on September 27 in the US.<ref name="blackparade" /> The single became the band's first number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]] in October 2006. ''[[The Black Parade]]'' was released on October 23, 2006, in the United Kingdom and on October 24, 2006, in the United States to positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/the-black-parade |title="The Black Parade" at Metacritic |publisher=Metacritic.com |access-date=2011-05-14 |archive-date=January 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111115401/http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-black-parade |url-status=live }}</ref> In the US, "Welcome to the Black Parade" reached number nine on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making it the band's only top ten hit to date on the chart.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=My Chemical Romance |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/my-chemical-romance/ |access-date=2022-07-05 |magazine=Billboard |language=en-US}}</ref> 
[[File:My Chemical Romance fire.jpg|thumb|Most of the concerts on The Black Parade World Tour involved the use of [[pyrotechnics]], especially during "Mama" and "[[Famous Last Words (My Chemical Romance song)|Famous Last Words]]".]]

''The Black Parade World Tour'' commenced on February 22, 2007, with the eventuating 133 shows featuring [[Rise Against]], [[Thursday (band)|Thursday]] and [[Muse (band)|Muse]] as support acts.<ref name="2007UStourdates">{{cite web|url=http://www.alternativepress.com/news/archive/page_7.htm |title= Alternative Press Magazine |publisher=Alternativepress.com |access-date=2010-03-13 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080511094105/http://www.alternativepress.com/news/archive/page_7.htm |archive-date = May 11, 2008}}</ref> [[Reggie and the Full Effect]] frontman [[James Dewees]] joined the band to play keyboards and synthesizer from there on. In April 2007, it was announced that Mikey Way would temporarily leave the tour to spend time with his new wife, Alicia Simmons-Way. Way's temporary replacement was Matt Cortez, a friend of the band.<ref name="Mikey Wedding">{{cite magazine | title=Gerard Way's brother leaves My Chemical Romance | date=2007-04-23 | magazine=NME | url=https://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/27856 | access-date=2007-04-23 | archive-date=March 4, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304054944/http://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/27856 | url-status=live }}</ref> During the third leg of the tour, as a support act for [[Muse (band)|Muse]], members of My Chemical Romance and their crew, along with members of Muse's crew, suffered [[food poisoning]], and consequently had to cancel six shows.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/my_chemical_romance_muse_poisoned.html |title=My Chemical Romance, Muse Poisoned |publisher=Ultimate-guitar.com |access-date=2014-07-27 |archive-date=May 4, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070504183502/http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/general_music_news/my_chemical_romance_muse_poisoned.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The band later featured on Linkin Park's ''[[Projekt Revolution]]'' tour in 2007,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wxdx.com/cc-common/mediaplayer/player.html?redir=yes&mps=Default&mid=http://a1135.g.akamai.net/f/1135/29458/1h/cchannel.download.akamai.com/29458/2094/richmedia/JoeLinkinpark.mp3?CCOMRRMID=2373244&CPROG=RICHMEDIA&MARKET=PITTSBURGH-PA&NG_FORMAT=alternative&NG_ID=wxdx105fm&OR_NEWSFORMAT=&OWNER=2094&SERVER_NAME=www.1059thex.com&SITE_ID=2094&STATION_ID=WXDX-FM&TRACK=lp_interview |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011122556/http://www.wxdx.com/cc-common/mediaplayer/player.html?redir=yes&mps=Default&mid=http%3A%2F%2Fa1135.g.akamai.net%2Ff%2F1135%2F29458%2F1h%2Fcchannel.download.akamai.com%2F29458%2F2094%2Frichmedia%2FJoeLinkinpark.mp3%3FCCOMRRMID%3D2373244&CPROG=RICHMEDIA&MARKET=PITTSBURGH-PA&NG_FORMAT=alternative&NG_ID=wxdx105fm&OR_NEWSFORMAT=&OWNER=2094&SERVER_NAME=www.1059thex.com&SITE_ID=2094&STATION_ID=WXDX-FM&TRACK=lp_interview |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 11, 2008 |title=Media Player |publisher=Wxdx.com |access-date=2010-03-13 }}</ref> along with [[Placebo (band)|Placebo]], [[Mindless Self Indulgence]], [[Saosin]], [[Taking Back Sunday]] and [[HIM (Finnish band)|HIM]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Aubin|last=Paul|url=https://www.punknews.org/article/23610/tours-projekt-revolution-with-my-chemical-romance-taking-back-sunday-bled|title=Projekt Revolution with My Chemical Romance, Taking Back Sunday, Bled|publisher=Punknews.org|access-date=July 24, 2018|archive-date=July 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725063730/https://www.punknews.org/article/23610/tours-projekt-revolution-with-my-chemical-romance-taking-back-sunday-bled|url-status=live}}</ref>

My Chemical Romance received a range of accolades for ''The Black Parade''. ''[[Kerrang!]]'' rated ''The Black Parade'' as the fourth-greatest album of 2006.<ref>''[[Kerrang!]]'' Magazine. Issue 1139.</ref> In ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's ranking of the top 50 albums of 2006, ''The Black Parade'' was voted the 20th best album of the year. My Chemical Romance went on to win the award for Best International Band at the 2007 [[NME Awards]], and Gerard Way also won the Hero of the Year award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/awardswinners2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070320124207/http://www.nme.com/awardswinners2007 |archive-date=2007-03-20 |title=NME Awards Winners of 2007 |publisher=Nme.com |access-date=2010-03-13}} Retrieved from archive – December 11, 2013.</ref> My Chemical Romance was also nominated for Best Alternative Group at the [[American Music Awards of 2007|2007 American Music Awards]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2022}}

The band announced in a blog on their website that they would be going on a final tour in the United States before taking a break. At the same time, they announced they will be releasing a live DVD/CD collection titled ''[[The Black Parade Is Dead!]]'', which includes two concerts from October 2007, the final Black Parade concert in Mexico, and a small show at Maxwell's in New Jersey. The DVD/CD was meant to be released on June 24 in the United States and June 30 in the UK, but was postponed to July 1 because of a technical fault with the Mexico concert.<ref name="Taste it TV interview">{{cite web |title=Interview with Gerard Way by Taste it TV, Luxemburg. November 2007 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AWB2TQJAovE |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418063538/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AWB2TQJAovE |archive-date=April 18, 2016 |access-date=November 27, 2016 |publisher=Taste it TV Youtube channel}}</ref> On February 3, 2009, an EP of B-side songs from singles on ''The Black Parade'' was released, titled ''[[The Black Parade: The B-Sides]]''. The band then announced that they would be releasing "a collection of nine never-before-seen live videos, straight from the encore set of the Mexico City show from October 2007" during their Black Parade World Tour, titled ''[[¡Venganza!]]''. The release came on a bullet-shaped [[USB flash drive|flash drive]] and also contained exclusive photos of the band from the show. It was released on April 29, 2009.<ref>{{cite web |title=Get "¡VENGANZA!" – 9 new live videos with USB and a vest |url=http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/jeff-watson/get-%C2%A1venganza-9-new-live-videos-usb-and-vest |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110121021726/http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/jeff-watson/get-%C2%A1venganza-9-new-live-videos-usb-and-vest |archive-date=January 21, 2011 |access-date=2010-03-13 |publisher=My Chemical Romance}}</ref>

==== ''Daily Mail'' controversy ====
{{See|Emo#Controversy and backlash}}

British [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] ''[[Daily Mail]]'' characterised the band and their fans as "[[emo]]" and a "[[cult]] of [[self-harm]]" in 2006.<ref name=":2" /> ''[[The Guardian]]'' described My Chemical Romance's perceived association with emo originated from "Iero's appearance, their debut being produced by a member of [[Thursday (band)|Thursday]], and the band members' openness about their [[Mental health issues|mental-health issues]]" while acknowledging major stylistic differences between emo and My Chemical Romance's music. The band disputed their association with emo and the characterisation of their music as dangerous, comparing it to controversies surrounding [[Judas Priest]] in the 1980s.<ref name=":2" /> The media attention, which coincided with the release of ''The Black Parade,'' is thought to have boosted the band's popularity in the UK.<ref name=":2" />

On May 16, 2008, the ''Daily Mail'' published an article titled "Why no child is safe from the sinister cult of emo".<ref name=":5">{{Cite web |title=We Are Not A Cult: Remembering the war on emo |url=https://www.kerrang.com/we-are-not-a-cult-remembering-the-war-on-emo/ |access-date=2022-05-23 |website=Kerrang! |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":6" /> It discussed the [[suicide]] of a thirteen-year-old British girl named Hannah Bond, who supposedly took her life because of her involvement in an "emo cult" which the newspaper directly associated with My Chemical Romance and their fans, and their then-current album ''[[The Black Parade]]''.<ref name=":5" /> The basis for the article was a statement by coroner Roger Sykes from the investigation into Bond's death, who expressed concern that her "emo" lifestyle glamorized suicide and suggested that her obsession with My Chemical Romance was linked to her death.<ref name="NME" /><ref name=":5" /> The ''Mail'' followed this with several stories also describing the band and emo as a "sinister cult" and "dangerous".<ref name=":3" /> Supporters of emo music contacted ''[[NME]]'' to defend the genre against accusations that it promotes suicide.<ref name="NME">{{cite magazine | url= https://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/36480 | magazine= NME | date= May 8, 2008 | title= Emo fans defend their music against suicide claims | access-date= April 21, 2020 | archive-date= April 11, 2016 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160411080233/http://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/36480 | url-status= live }}</ref> The band responded by paying tribute to Bond, saying that their music is "anti-violence and anti-suicide" and aiming to provide comfort and solace to fans, and encouraged fans experiencing feelings of [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] or suicide to seek help.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2008-05-27 |title=My Chemical Romance defend emo |language=en-GB |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/hi/music/newsid_7421000/7421328.stm |access-date=2022-05-23}}</ref>

A group of British fans eventually planned a march across London in protest against the depiction of the band in the media. The march was expected to be held on May 31, beginning at [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]]'s West Pond and ending outside the offices of the ''[[Daily Mail]]''. The march was expected to attract 500–1,000 protesters, according to the organizers.<ref>{{cite magazine | url= https://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/36745 | magazine= NME | date= May 21, 2008 | title= Fans march against The Daily Mail | access-date= April 21, 2020 | archive-date= March 3, 2016 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160303200854/http://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/36745 | url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine| url= https://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/36848| magazine= NME| date= May 26, 2008| title= My Chemical Romance march 'aiming for 1,000 protestors'| access-date= April 21, 2020| archive-date= March 3, 2016| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160303220135/http://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/36848| url-status= live}}</ref> After concerns by police, the march was called off and instead about 100 fans congregated at [[Marble Arch]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Fitzsimmons |first=Caitlin |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/may/31/dailymail.musicnews?gusrc=rss&feed=media |title=Emo runs high as fans defend band against Daily Mail |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=2010-03-13 |location=London |date=May 31, 2008 |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304062700/http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/may/31/dailymail.musicnews?gusrc=rss&feed=media |url-status=live }}</ref> The band repeated the statement "fuck the ''Daily Mail''" during their gigs in the [[United Kingdom]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2022}}

''The Daily Mail'' defended its position saying its coverage was "balanced and restrained" and "in the public interest" and that they were reporting genuine concerns raised by the coroner at the inquest. They stated that their coverage of the coroner's remarks and the parents' comments was in common with that of other newspapers and pointed to their publishing of readers' letters defending the band and positive reviews of the band's albums and tours.<ref name=":3">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/my-chemical-romance-106-1334107|title=Daily Mail respond to My Chemical Romance emo marchers – NME|website=[[NME]]|date=May 31, 2008|access-date=April 21, 2020|archive-date=February 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216172211/https://www.nme.com/news/music/my-chemical-romance-106-1334107|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Kerrang!|Kerrang]]'' later described the original story as having a "heavy-handed approach and factual inaccuracies" and demonised the emo [[subculture]].<ref name=":5" /> In a 2022 retrospective, ''The Guardian'' described the backlash against the band and emo music as a "[[moral panic]]".<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |date=2022-05-10 |title=My Chemical Romance: how the vilified band turned antipathy into triumph |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2022/may/10/my-chemical-romance-how-the-vilified-band-turned-antipathy-into-triumph |access-date=2022-05-22 |website=the Guardian |language=en}}</ref>

===''Danger Days: The True Lives of the Fabulous Killjoys'' (2009–2011)===
{{Main|Danger Days: The True Lives of the Fabulous Killjoys}}

On February 1, 2009, My Chemical Romance released a new single titled "[[Desolation Row#Other recordings|Desolation Row]]" (a [[cover version|cover]] of the [[Bob Dylan]] song). It was recorded to feature as the end credit track for the 2009 film ''[[Watchmen (film)|Watchmen]]'', an adaptation of the [[Watchmen|graphic novel of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thrashhits.com/2009/01/new-my-chemical-romance-single-desolation-row-on-xfm-first/ |title=New My Chemical Romance single, 'Desolation Row' on Xfm first |publisher=Thrashhits.com |access-date=2010-03-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213161442/http://www.thrashhits.com/2009/01/new-my-chemical-romance-single-desolation-row-on-xfm-first/ |archive-date=2012-02-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

On May 27, 2009, My Chemical Romance's web designer, Jeff Watson, announced via the band's website that the band was headed to the studio to record their fourth full-length album. The recording took place over the following few weeks with producer [[Brendan O'Brien (music producer)|Brendan O'Brien]], who has worked with [[AC/DC]], [[Mastodon (band)|Mastodon]], and [[Pearl Jam]].

In an interview with ''NME'', Gerard Way said the band's next record would be a rock album, saying, "I think [the next album] will definitely be stripped down. I think the band misses being a rock band."<ref name="Interview with Gerard">{{cite web |url=http://ultimate-guitar.com/news/upcoming_releases/my_chemical_romance_promise_punk_rock_album.html |title=My Chemical Romance Promise 'Punk Rock' Album |publisher=Ultimate-guitar.com |access-date=2014-07-27 |archive-date=February 2, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080202075201/http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/upcoming_releases/my_chemical_romance_promise_punk_rock_album.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In a separate interview with ''[[Idiomag]]'', Way commented that the next release would be less theatrical in scope, stating that "it's not going to be hiding behind a veil of fiction or uniforms and makeup anymore."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idiomag.com/peek/65600/my_chemical_romance|title=My Chemical Romance on New Record: Less Drama, No Makeup|access-date=2009-02-19|date=2009-02-18|publisher=[[idiomag]]|archive-date=February 24, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224172151/http://www.idiomag.com/peek/65600/my_chemical_romance|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with PopEater, Way also stated that the next album will be "full of hate". He also said "over the years that we've been hearing ourselves live and hearing us on records, we kind of prefer the live. There's more of a garage feel and more energy. I'd like to capture some of that, finally. That's the goal for the next one."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popeater.com/music/article/my-chemical-romance-full-of-hate-on-new/220047 |title=My Chemical Romance Full of Hate |publisher=Popeater |access-date=2009-06-30 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205185301/http://www.popeater.com/music/article/my-chemical-romance-full-of-hate-on-new/220047 |archive-date=February 5, 2009 }}</ref>

On July 31 and August 1, 2009, My Chemical Romance played two "secret" shows at The Roxy Theater in Los Angeles. The shows were the first concerts the band had played since [[Madison Square Garden]] in May 2008. The band also premiered several new songs said to be from their upcoming fourth album during the shows, one reportedly titled "Death Before Disco", a song that Way said he was particularly excited about.<ref name="MCR plays at Roxy">{{cite news | title=My Chemical Romance's New Album Is A 'Love Letter To Rock And Roll' | publisher=MTV | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1617488/20090803/my_chemical_romance.jhtml | access-date=August 6, 2009 | archive-date=August 4, 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090804212819/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1617488/20090803/my_chemical_romance.jhtml | url-status=live }}</ref> The song was since renamed "Party Poison" and was included on the new album. Way explained further in a ''Rolling Stone'' interview that "it's a completely different sound for the band&nbsp;— it's like an anti-party song that you can party to. I can't wait for people to hear it. It brings back, lyrically, some of that wonderful fiction from the first album."<ref name="MCR">{{cite magazine | title=Gerard Way Talks New Comic "Fabulous Killjoys," Next My Chemical Romance Album | magazine=Rolling Stone | url =https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/29344851/gerard_way_talks_new_comic_fabulous_killjoys_next_my_chemical_romance_album | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20090729083025/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/29344851/gerard_way_talks_new_comic_fabulous_killjoys_next_my_chemical_romance_album | url-status =dead | archive-date =July 29, 2009 | access-date = July 27, 2009 }}</ref>

[[Gerard Way]] also said in a November 2009 interview with ''[[Rock Sound]]'' that the fourth album would be their defining work. "A friend who heard the record recently said he now had no interest in listening to our older work anymore, that we had made all our old material redundant. I took it as a compliment, the next thing you should always make the last thing seem unimportant and I think that will happen when we finally release this album."<ref name="Rock Sound">{{cite magazine | title=My Chemical Romance Talk About Album Four | magazine=[[Rock Sound]] | url=http://www.rocksound.tv/news/article/my-chemical-romance-talk-about-album-four | access-date=November 12, 2009 | archive-date=November 13, 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091113111042/http://www.rocksound.tv/news/article/my-chemical-romance-talk-about-album-four | url-status=live }}</ref>

On March 3, 2010, Iero announced on their official website that Bob Bryar had left the band, writing:

{{blockquote|As of 4 weeks ago, My Chemical Romance and [[Bob Bryar]] parted ways. This was a painful decision for all of us to make and was not taken lightly. We wish him the best of luck in his future endeavors and expect you all to do the same.|Frank Iero<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/frank/one-chapter-ends-and-another-begins |title=One chapter ends and another begins ...|publisher=My Chemical Romance |date=2010-03-03 |access-date=2010-03-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100307013124/http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/frank/one-chapter-ends-and-another-begins |archive-date=2010-03-07 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altpress.com/news/8574.htm |title=AP: NEWS – Bob Bryar out of My Chemical Romance |publisher=Altpress.com |access-date=2010-03-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312112709/http://www.altpress.com/news/8574.htm |archive-date=2010-03-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}

In a March 2010 [[MTV]] interview about the new album, Way explained, "There's no title yet ... I'm actually kind of excited about that. It's kind of 'anything goes' at this point, but I'm so happy with the songs." Though the band since decided on the title of their fourth album, it continued to go unannounced, with various rumors circulating and the band stating on their website that it will be revealed "all in due time"<ref name="To Kill a Demon Shark" /> and in Way's words, "a special way this time. Maybe some sort of event, something fun, something soon."

During the San Diego [[San Diego Comic-Con International|Comic-Con]] 2010, Way announced that the band had finished recording the fourth studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rAGYRnABLBk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401132820/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rAGYRnABLBk|archive-date=April 1, 2016|title=Gerard Way introduction – Dark Horse panel – Comic Con 2010|publisher=Youtube|access-date=2010-08-04|url-status=live}}</ref> This was later confirmed by Iero on the band's website, announcing that the album was "done, finished, kaput, in the proverbial can, and being played loudly as we drive way too fast in our respective cars."<ref name="To Kill a Demon Shark">{{cite news | first=Frank | last=Iero | title=To Kill A Demon Shark | date=2010-09-07 | publisher=mychemicalromance.com | url=http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/frank/kill-demon-shark | access-date=2010-09-10 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100913213759/http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/frank/kill-demon-shark | archive-date=2010-09-13 }}</ref>

In September, a trailer video was uploaded to My Chemical Romance's official [[YouTube]] page titled ''Art is a Weapon'', which announced the title of the album: ''[[Danger Days: The True Lives of the Fabulous Killjoys]]''. The video featured the band wearing strangely coloured outfits and battling unusual characters in a desert surrounding, and featuring a sample of music from the song "[[Na Na Na (Na Na Na Na Na Na Na Na Na)]]". Notable comic book author and the band's personal friend, [[Grant Morrison]], makes a special appearance, in the role of an enemy and leader of a band of masked characters. On September 22, 2010, the band premiered their song "Na Na Na (Na Na Na Na Na Na Na Na Na)" on [[Zane Lowe]]'s [[BBC Radio 1]] show, and [[Los Angeles]]-based radio station [[KROQ-FM]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=1923042 |title=My Chemical Romance New Song and Interview |website=AbsolutePunk |date=2010-09-22 |access-date=2010-09-22 |archive-date=July 7, 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120707064528/http://absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=1923042 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://kroq.radio.com/2010/09/22/world-premiere-my-chemical-romance-na-na-na/ |title=World Premiere: My Chemical Romance "Na Na Na" |publisher=KROQ-FM |date=2010-09-22 |access-date=2010-09-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925193758/http://kroq.radio.com/2010/09/22/world-premiere-my-chemical-romance-na-na-na/ |archive-date=2010-09-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The album was released on November 22, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/my_chemical_romance/albums.jhtml?albumId=2652454 |title=Danger Days: The True Lives of the Fabulous Killjoys &#124; My Chemical Romance &#124; Album |publisher=MTV |access-date=2011-11-04}}</ref>

''Rock Sound'' had a preview of the album and gave a positive review, commenting "the way they've used everything they learned on ''The Black Parade'' and tightened up in certain places feels natural and confident" and that it sees "the creativity of the band taking flight musically, graphically and literally."<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.rocksound.tv/blog/article/my-chemical-romances-danger-days-heres-what-you-need-to-know |title=My Chemical Romance's 'Danger Days ... ' – Here's What You Need To Know |magazine=[[Rock Sound]] |date=2010-09-29 |access-date=2010-09-29 |archive-date=October 2, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101002145223/http://www.rocksound.tv/blog/article/my-chemical-romances-danger-days-heres-what-you-need-to-know |url-status=live }}</ref>

Michael Pedicone joined the band as a touring drummer late in 2010, replacing Bryar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1650748/20101025/my_chemical_romance.jhtml |title=My Chemical Romance introduce new Killjoy, Michael Pedicone |publisher=MTV |date=2010-10-25 |access-date=2010-10-25 |archive-date=October 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101028025059/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1650748/20101025/my_chemical_romance.jhtml |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[File:Wikimcrnotts.jpg|thumbnail|My Chemical Romance performing at a concert in 2011]]
During a performance at Wembley Arena on February 12, 2011, Way announced that the band would be appearing at a UK festival later in the year,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicrooms.net/rock/26558-my-chemical-romance-s-gerard-way-lets-slip-forthcoming-festival-appearance.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110222225338/http://www.musicrooms.net/rock/26558-my-chemical-romance-s-gerard-way-lets-slip-forthcoming-festival-appearance.html |archive-date=2011-02-22 |title=My Chemical Romance's Gerard Way lets slip forthcoming festival appearance |publisher=[[Music Sales Group]] |date=2011-02-14 |access-date=2011-02-14}} Retrieved from Internet Archive February 16, 2014.</ref> later confirmed as the [[Reading and Leeds Festivals]], which they headlined. They also performed at [[Radio 1's Big Weekend]] in [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]], England on May 15, 2011.

On September 2, 2011, Frank Iero posted a blog on the band's site stating, "The relationship between My Chemical Romance and Michael Pedicone is over" and explaining Pedicone was sacked because "he was caught red-handed stealing from the band and confessed to police after our show last night in Auburn, Washington." He also mentioned his hope of getting a new drummer in time for their next show and avoiding having to cancel any performances in the process.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/59014 |title=My Chemical Romance sack drummer Mike Pedicone over theft claims |publisher=Nme.com |access-date=2014-07-27 |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304044613/http://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/59014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="mychemicalromance1">{{cite web |url=http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/frank/just-facts |title=Just The Facts |publisher=My Chemical Romance |date=2011-09-02 |access-date=2011-11-04 |archive-date=April 26, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426162656/http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/frank/just-facts |url-status=live }}</ref>

On September 4, 2011, it was revealed through various sources that [[Jarrod Alexander]] will be the new touring drummer for the remainder of the Honda Civic tour. He also performed with them in late October at [[Voodoo Experience]] and at their Australian + New Zealand shows at [[Big Day Out]] in early 2012.

===''Conventional Weapons'' and break-up (2011–2013)===
{{Main|Conventional Weapons}}

In an interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in October 2011, guitarist [[Frank Iero]] revealed that new music could be out "by summer".<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Steve|first=Baltin|title=My Chemical Romance's Frank Iero Designs Guitar for Charity|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/my-chemical-romances-frank-iero-designs-guitar-for-charity-20111011|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=March 25, 2012|archive-date=April 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414124930/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/my-chemical-romances-frank-iero-designs-guitar-for-charity-20111011|url-status=live}}</ref>

On April 28, 2011, US broadcaster [[Glenn Beck]] labelled the My Chemical Romance song "[[Sing (My Chemical Romance song)|Sing]]" as "[[propaganda]]" after it was featured and covered on the US musical drama TV series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' in February 2011. Beck stated "It's an anthem saying 'Join us'. How can you and I possibly win against that?"
The lyrics that Beck pointed out were: "Cleaned up corporation progress, dying in the process / Children that can talk about it living on the railways {{sic}} / People moving sideways / Sell it till your last days / Buy yourself the motivation / Generation nothing / Nothing but a dead scene / Product of a white dream". Gerard Way responded to the accusation on the band's official website, writing, "I think the word Glenn Beck was looking for was 'subversion' not 'propaganda', because I don't know what it would be considered propaganda for—truth? Sentiment?" He also said that he was "shocked that no actual fact-checking was done on the lyrics".<ref name="Guardian Spat">{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=Dan|title=My Chemical Romance enter spat with US pundit Glenn Beck|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/may/05/my-chemical-romance-glenn-beck|access-date=March 14, 2018|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News & Media Ltd|date=May 5, 2011|archive-date=March 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174221/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/may/05/my-chemical-romance-glenn-beck|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="MTV News Propaganda">{{cite news|last1=Montgomery|first1=James|title=My Chemical Romance's 'Sing' Is 'Propaganda,' Glenn Beck Says|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1662964/my-chemical-romance-glenn-beck-sing/|access-date=March 14, 2018|work=MTV News|date=April 29, 2011|archive-date=March 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174322/http://www.mtv.com/news/1662964/my-chemical-romance-glenn-beck-sing/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Westword Predictable">{{cite news|last1=Otte|first1=Jef|title=Glenn Beck's crazy but surprising, while My Chemical Romance is just predictable|url=http://www.westword.com/music/glenn-becks-crazy-but-surprising-while-my-chemical-romance-is-just-predictable-5112681|access-date=March 14, 2018|work=Westword|date=May 11, 2011|archive-date=March 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314174152/http://www.westword.com/music/glenn-becks-crazy-but-surprising-while-my-chemical-romance-is-just-predictable-5112681|url-status=live}}</ref> Bassist Mikey Way told the BBC, "If we're getting reaction from people like that we're doing something right."<ref name="BBC Glee critics">{{cite web|title=My Chemical Romance respond to Glee critics in America|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/13427069/my-chemical-romance-respond-to-glee-critics-in-america|website=Newsbeat|publisher=BBC|access-date=March 13, 2018|date=May 17, 2011|archive-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616074647/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/13427069/my-chemical-romance-respond-to-glee-critics-in-america|url-status=live}}</ref>

On December 18, 2011, the band appeared on [[Nick Jr.]]'s ''[[Yo Gabba Gabba!]]'', and performed a song called "Every Snowflake Is Different (Just Like You)". This was part of a Christmas special for the show. The special included other famous guests such as [[Tony Hawk]] and [[Tori Spelling]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Anderson|first=Kyle|title=Watch My Chemical Romance perform 'Every Snowflake Is Different (Just Like You)' on 'Yo Gabba Gabba!': An EW video exclusive!|url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2011/12/06/my-chemical-romance-yo-gabba-gabba/|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=December 18, 2012|archive-date=January 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119090037/http://music-mix.ew.com/2011/12/06/my-chemical-romance-yo-gabba-gabba/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=My Chemical Romance on Yo Gabba Gabba!|url=http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/mcr/my-chemical-romance-yo-gabba-gabba|publisher=My Chemical Romance|access-date=December 18, 2012|archive-date=April 16, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120416010534/http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/mcr/my-chemical-romance-yo-gabba-gabba|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Gerard Way Big Day Out 2012 2.jpg|thumb|Gerard Way at the festival [[Big Day Out]] in February 2012 in [[Australia]]]]
In February 2012, members of My Chemical Romance revealed that they had been building a studio in [[Los Angeles]] to record music for the band's fifth album under the working title MCR5, now with touring keyboardist James Dewees as an official member.<ref>{{cite web |title=James Dewees – How I Joined My Chemical Romance |date=June 6, 2012 |url=https://www.rolandus.com/blog/2012/06/06/james-dewees-how-i-joined-my-chemical-romance/ |publisher=[[Roland Corporation|Roland]] |access-date=26 December 2019 |quote=I've been their touring keyboardist for, you know, so many years and now I'm just ''the'' keyboardist |archive-date=December 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226180114/https://www.rolandus.com/blog/2012/06/06/james-dewees-how-i-joined-my-chemical-romance/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The band worked with engineer Doug McKean, who previously worked on ''[[The Black Parade]]'' and ''[[Danger Days: The True Lives of the Fabulous Killjoys]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tim|first=Cashmere|title=My Chemical Romance Build Studio For Album Number Five|date=February 2012|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/my-chemical-romance-build-studio-for-album-number-five-20120201|publisher=Noise11|access-date=March 25, 2012|archive-date=March 10, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310192504/http://www.noise11.com/news/my-chemical-romance-build-studio-for-album-number-five-20120201|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 14, 2012, Frank Iero announced through the band's official website a new project titled ''Conventional Weapons''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tim|first=Cashmere|title=My Chemical Romance Announces Conventional Weapons|url=http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/frank/conventional-weapons/|access-date=September 14, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916183638/http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/frank/conventional-weapons/?cmpid=20120914%2Fmcr%2Ffb%2Fcwannounce%2Fnews|archive-date=September 16, 2012}}</ref> The project revolved around 10 unreleased songs that were recorded in 2009, prior to the making of ''Danger Days''. The band released two songs each month for five months from the ''Conventional Weapons sessions'', starting in October 2012 and finishing in February 2013. According to the October 2012 issue of ''[[Q (magazine)|Q magazine]]'', Frank Iero reported early sessions for MCR's next album with the new drummer Jarrod Alexander were progressing well. "Jarrod is a rad guy and a fantastic player. It's been really fun making music with him these past few months," Iero commented.<ref name="q_dec_2012">Q magazine. October 2012. Coming Up / Also Tweaking. P. 23</ref>

On March 22, 2013, the band announced their break-up on their official website,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mychemicalromance.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325024121/http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/mcr/my-chemical-romance|url-status=dead|title=My Chemical Romance - MY CHEMICAL ROMANCE Official Blog|archive-date=March 25, 2013|website=MY CHEMICAL ROMANCE Official Website}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alterthepress.com/2013/03/my-chemical-romance-break-up.html |title=My Chemical Romance Announce Their Break Up |publisher=Alterthepress.com |access-date=2014-07-27 |archive-date=March 26, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130326003601/http://www.alterthepress.com/2013/03/my-chemical-romance-break-up.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://pupfresh.com/post/46042398532 |title=Rip My Chemical Romance |publisher=Pup Fresh |access-date=2014-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325232346/http://pupfresh.com/post/46042398532 |archive-date=March 25, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> issuing this statement:

{{blockquote|Being in this band for the past 12 years has been a true blessing. We've gotten to go places we never knew we would. We've been able to see and experience things we never imagined possible. We've shared the stage with people we admire, people we look up to, and best of all, our friends. And now, like all great things, it has come time for it to end. Thanks for all of your support, and for being part of the adventure.}}

Gerard Way posted an extended tweet on his Twitter account two days after the website announcement, in which he confirmed the disbanding of the group but denied that altercations between band members were the reason for the split.<ref>[http://www.kerrang.com/blog/2013/03/mcr_split_gerard_confirms_brea.html] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328081831/http://www.kerrang.com/blog/2013/03/mcr_split_gerard_confirms_brea.html |date=March 28, 2013 }}</ref>

===''May Death Never Stop You'' and post-breakup (2013–2019)===
On March 25, 2014, the band released a greatest hits collection, titled ''[[May Death Never Stop You]]'', containing material spreading their entire career, as well a single unreleased track.<ref name="kerrang1" /> The track "[[Fake Your Death]]" was made available digitally on February 17.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/may-death-never-stop-you-the-greatest-hits-2001-2013-mw0002616758 |title=May Death Never Stop You – My Chemical Romance |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=March 25, 2014 |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |author-link=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |archive-date=March 27, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327020546/http://www.allmusic.com/album/may-death-never-stop-you-the-greatest-hits-2001-2013-mw0002616758 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is the only song in MCR's discography having [[James Dewees]] playing on keyboards.

Following the band's breakup, the members of the band continued to pursue music. Lead vocalist [[Gerard Way]] announced his debut solo album ''[[Hesitant Alien]]'' with the release of an advance-single, "[[Action Cat]]".<ref>{{Cite web|title = Gerard Way premieres new song, "Action Cat" – News – Alternative Press|url = http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/gerard_way_premiering_new_song_action_cat|website = Alternative Press|date = June 11, 2014|access-date = November 4, 2015|archive-date = November 26, 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151126103205/http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/gerard_way_premiering_new_song_action_cat|url-status = live}}</ref> ''Hesitant Alien'' was released on September 29, 2014, in the UK, and a day later in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Gerard Way – Hesitant Alien|url = http://www.teamrock.com/reviews/2014-09-09/gerard-way-hesitant-alien|website = TeamRock|date = September 9, 2014|access-date = 2015-11-04|archive-date = December 8, 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151208101045/http://www.teamrock.com/reviews/2014-09-09/gerard-way-hesitant-alien|url-status = live}}</ref> ''Hesitant Alien'' was a moderate commercial success, topping the US [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] Alternative Albums chart and reaching No. 16 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Hesitant Alien – Gerard Way {{!}} Awards {{!}} AllMusic|url = https://www.allmusic.com/album/mw0002711565/awards|website = AllMusic|access-date = November 4, 2015|archive-date = December 8, 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151208170302/http://www.allmusic.com/album/mw0002711565/awards|url-status = live}}</ref> ''Hesitant Alien'' also topped the "Ten Essential Albums Of 2014" list in ''Alternative Press''.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Gerard Way – Hesitant Alien – Reviews – Alternative Press|url = http://www.altpress.com/reviews/entry/gerard_way_hesitant_alien|website = Alternative Press|date = September 9, 2014|access-date = November 4, 2015|archive-date = October 1, 2014|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141001085837/http://www.altpress.com/reviews/entry/gerard_way_hesitant_alien|url-status = live}}</ref>

Rhythm guitarist [[Frank Iero]] sporadically collaborated with My Chemical Romance keyboardist [[James Dewees]], forming [[Death Spells]] and performing in [[Reggie and the Full Effect]] (alongside Ray Toro), releasing ''[[No Country for Old Musicians]]'' on November 19, 2013. Afterwards, he announced via his official website that he signed to Staple Records and would be releasing a full-length solo album titled ''[[Stomachaches (album)|Stomachaches]]'' under the moniker of "frnkiero andthe cellabration". The album featured former My Chemical Romance touring drummer [[Jarrod Alexander]]. ''Stomachaches'' was released worldwide on August 25, 2014.<ref name="Digital release info">{{cite web|title=Frnkiero and the Cellabration Stomachaches (Digital Download – Vagrant #)|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/release/stomachaches-mr0004255996|website=AllMusic.com|publisher=AllMusic|access-date=September 15, 2014|archive-date=March 14, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314211516/http://www.allmusic.com/album/release/stomachaches-mr0004255996|url-status=live}}</ref>

Bassist [[Mikey Way]] formed Electric Century along with [[Sleep Station]] vocalist David Debiak in 2014 and released their debut single "I Lied" in February 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Electric Century – "I Lied" (SONG PREMIERE) – Features – Alternative Press|url = http://www.altpress.com/features/entry/electric_century_i_lied_song_premiere|website = Alternative Press|date = February 24, 2014|access-date = November 4, 2015|archive-date = January 8, 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160108170122/http://www.altpress.com/features/entry/electric_century_i_lied_song_premiere|url-status = live}}</ref> The duo announced their debut [[Electric Century (EP)|self-titled EP]] on March 10, 2015, and it was released on [[Record Store Day]] on April 18, 2015.

Lead guitarist [[Ray Toro]] posted a song on his [[SoundCloud]] account titled "Isn't That Something" on May 24, 2013. On January 1, 2015, he posted a new song, titled "For the Lost and Brave", on his website, dedicating the song to [[Death of Leelah Alcorn|Leelah Alcorn]], a transgender teen who committed suicide.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Leelah Alcorn: Ray Toro dedicates song 'For The Lost And The Brave' to 17-year-old transgender female who committed suicide|url = http://www.wcpo.com/news/local-news/warren-county/my-chemical-romances-ray-toro-dedicates-song-to-leelah-alcorn|website = WCPO|access-date = November 4, 2015|url-status = dead|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160913082821/http://www.wcpo.com/news/local-news/warren-county/my-chemical-romances-ray-toro-dedicates-song-to-leelah-alcorn|archive-date = 2016-09-13}}</ref>
<!-- Mention only notable events/releases taken place RECENTLY AFTER THE BAND'S SPLIT until here. Other info years after then (reunions, collaborations, etc) go past this note -->

On July 20, 2016, the band posted on their official [[Twitter]] and [[Facebook]] pages a video with the piano intro from "[[Welcome to the Black Parade]]", ending with a cryptic date, "9/23/16".<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Are My Chemical Romance Getting Back Together?|url=http://www.kerrang.com/44497/chemical-romance-getting-back-together/|magazine=[[Kerrang!]]|access-date=July 20, 2016|archive-date=July 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721115053/http://www.kerrang.com/44497/chemical-romance-getting-back-together/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=My Chemical Romance post new logo and cryptic date|url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/my_chemical_romance_post_new_logo_and_cryptic_date|magazine=[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]|access-date=July 20, 2016|archive-date=September 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922105540/http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/my_chemical_romance_post_new_logo_and_cryptic_date|url-status=live}}</ref> The video was also published on the band's [[YouTube]] channel with the video titled "MCRX".<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7wIKQS9Df48| archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/7wIKQS9Df48?url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7wIKQS9Df48| archive-date=2021-09-24|title=MCRX|date=July 20, 2016|via=YouTube}}</ref> This led to numerous rumors and reports on the band's possible reunion until it was revealed to be a reissue of ''[[The Black Parade]]'' with unreleased demos.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/07/20/my-chemical-romance-tease-september|title=My Chemical Romance reissuing famed album The Black Parade after cryptic tweet|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|author=Bacle, Ariana|date=July 20, 2016|access-date=July 21, 2016|archive-date=July 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721132144/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/07/20/my-chemical-romance-tease-september|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/07/my-chemical-romance-hint-at-reunion-for-10th-anniversary-of-the-black-parade/|title=My Chemical Romance hint at reunion for 10th anniversary of The Black Parade|magazine=[[Consequence of Sound]]|author=Brennan, Collin|date=July 20, 2016|access-date=July 21, 2016|archive-date=July 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721123959/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/07/my-chemical-romance-hint-at-reunion-for-10th-anniversary-of-the-black-parade/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/95157|title=Is the My Chemical Romance comeback a 10th anniversary 'The Black Parade' reissue?|magazine=[[NME]]|author=Britton, Luke Morgan|date=July 21, 2016|access-date=July 21, 2016|archive-date=July 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722130758/http://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/95157|url-status=live}}</ref> The reissue, titled ''[[The Black Parade/Living with Ghosts]]'',<ref>{{cite magazine|title=My Chemical Romance to Release 'The Black Parade' Deluxe Reissue|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/my-chemical-romance-to-release-the-black-parade-deluxe-reissue-w431683|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=July 30, 2016|archive-date=July 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731001733/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/my-chemical-romance-to-release-the-black-parade-deluxe-reissue-w431683|url-status=live}}</ref> includes 11 demos and live tracks. Two months before its release, an early version of "Welcome to the Black Parade", titled "The Five of Us Are Dying", was made available for streaming.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/95310|title=Stream My Chemical Romance's previously unreleased track 'The Five Of Us Are Dying'|magazine=[[NME]]|author=Britton, Luke Morgan|date=July 29, 2016|access-date=July 29, 2016|archive-date=July 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729172441/http://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/95310|url-status=live}}</ref>

In a discussion of his work on the comic book ''[[Doom Patrol]]'', Gerard Way told ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', "I wouldn't count (a reunion) out, but at the same time everybody's doing stuff in their lives now that they're really enjoying."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Graff|first1=Gary|title=Gerard Way Shares 'Doom Patrol' Exclusive Sketches, Talks 'Personal Attachment' to the Comic|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7817713/gerard-way-doom-patrol-comic-sketches|access-date=June 8, 2017|magazine=Billboard|date=June 8, 2017|archive-date=June 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607235041/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7817713/gerard-way-doom-patrol-comic-sketches|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Reunion and new material (2019–present)===
{{Main|My Chemical Romance Reunion Tour}}
[[File:My Chemical Romance Shrine Expo Hall Los Angeles return show 2019.jpg|thumb|My Chemical Romance performing at their 2019 reunion show.]]
On October 31, 2019, the band announced they would be reuniting in [[Los Angeles]] on December 20 and a new merchandise line. The announcement was accompanied by the captions "Return" and "Like Phantoms Forever...".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B4SyPJKBvAr/|title=Like Phantoms Forever... Tickets on Sale Friday 11/1/19 at 12:00 PM Pacific|via=[[Instagram]]|access-date=October 31, 2019|archive-date=November 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101170718/https://www.instagram.com/p/B4SyPJKBvAr/|url-status=live}}</ref> The show sold out in 4 minutes despite high ticket prices. Believed initially to be a one-off show, almost a week later, the band announced more dates in Australia, Japan and New Zealand for 2020.<ref name="Campbell">{{Cite web |last=Campbell |first=Rachel |date=2019-11-05 |title=My Chemical Romance announce two more reunion shows—UPDATED |url=https://www.altpress.com/news/my-chemical-romance-australia-new-zealand-japan-2020-dates/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191106061005/https://www.altpress.com/news/my-chemical-romance-australia-new-zealand-japan-2020-dates/ |archive-date=November 6, 2019 |access-date=2019-11-06 |website=Alternative Press |language=en-US}}</ref> They later revealed via Twitter that they had first regrouped in 2017 and had been working together since then, before the official 2019 announcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MCRofficial/status/1207909921930371072|title=My Chemical Romance Official Twitter|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20|archive-date=November 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201111234423/https://twitter.com/MCRofficial/status/1207909921930371072?s=19|url-status=live}}</ref> The concert grossed $1,451,745, with an attendance of 5,113.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/current-boxscore|title=Current Boxscore &#124; Billboard|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=August 7, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200122032404/https://www.billboard.com/charts/current-boxscore |access-date=January 22, 2020|archive-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>

In January 2020, the group announced plans to present one, then two, then three concerts at [[Stadium MK]] ([[Milton Keynes]], [[England]]), on the 18th, 20th and 21 June 2020, as tickets for each day sold out within minutes.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/my-chemical-romance-2020-uk-tour-dates-tickets-milton-keynes-a4338766.html | title= My Chemical Romance 2020 UK tour: Milton Keynes dates, ticket information and venues | newspaper= [[Evening Standard]] | author= Tom Herbert, Emma Clarke | date= 28 January 2020 | access-date= 28 January 2020 | archive-date= January 28, 2020 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200128110628/https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/my-chemical-romance-2020-uk-tour-dates-tickets-milton-keynes-a4338766.html | url-status= live }}</ref>  The stadium has an (all round) capacity of 30,500 for sports events. Later in the month, the group premiered a cryptic video on YouTube which ended by announcing a North American tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6478872/my-chemical-romance-reunion-tour-2020/|title=My Chemical Romance announces first North American tour in 9 years, 1 Canadian date|publisher=Global News|date=January 29, 2020|access-date=January 31, 2020|archive-date=January 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130135654/https://globalnews.ca/news/6478872/my-chemical-romance-reunion-tour-2020/|url-status=live}}</ref> The North American shows went on sale on January 31, 2020, and sold out in less than six hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/the-news/my-chemical-romance-sells-out-north-american-tour-in-under-six-hours/|title=My Chemical Romance Sells Out North American Tour In Under Six Hours|publisher=Kerrang!|date=January 31, 2020|access-date=February 2, 2020|archive-date=February 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202185952/https://www.kerrang.com/the-news/my-chemical-romance-sells-out-north-american-tour-in-under-six-hours/|url-status=live}}</ref> Due to the ongoing [[COVID-19 pandemic]], all of the shows on the tour that were set to begin in 2020 were [[Impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on the music industry|postponed]] to 2021, including the North American leg.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/06/my-chemical-romance-reschedule-reunion-tour-2021/|title=My Chemical Romance Reschedule Reunion Tour for 2021|publisher=Consequence of Sound|date=June 16, 2020|access-date=June 16, 2020|archive-date=June 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200617030222/https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/06/my-chemical-romance-reschedule-reunion-tour-2021/|url-status=live}}</ref> These tour dates were later rescheduled again to 2022.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Kreps |first1=Daniel |title=My Chemical Romance Postpone Reunion Tour to 2022 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/my-chemical-romance-postpone-tour-2022-1156983/ |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=April 19, 2021 |date=April 16, 2021 |archive-date=April 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419142753/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/my-chemical-romance-postpone-tour-2022-1156983/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The tour commenced on 16 May 2022 at the [[Eden Project]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-05-22 |title=My Chemical Romance pay tribute to Power Trip's Riley Gale at Milton Keynes show |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/my-chemical-romance-pay-tribute-to-power-trips-riley-gale-at-milton-keynes-show-3230734 |access-date=2022-05-23 |website=NME |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On May 12, 2022, the band released "[[The Foundations of Decay]]", their first new song since 2014.<ref>{{cite web|first=Matthew|last=Strauss|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/my-chemical-romance-share-first-new-song-since-2014-listen/|title=My Chemical Romance Share First New Song Since 2014: Listen|website=Pitchfork|date=May 12, 2022|access-date=May 12, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Merlin|last=Alderslade|url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/listen-to-brand-new-my-chemical-romance-single-the-foundations-of-decay-right-now|title=Listen to brand new My Chemical Romance single The Foundations Of Decay right now|website=Louder Sound|date=May 12, 2022|access-date=May 12, 2022}}</ref>

