}}}} The band's official website describes their music as simply "rock" or "violent, dangerous [[pop music|pop]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mychemicalromance.com/mcrhtml/band.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060816052539/http://mychemicalromance.com/mcrhtml/band.html|title=Official website Band Biography|access-date=September 15, 2006|archive-date=August 16, 2006}}</ref> Gerard Way has publicly rejected the term "emo",<ref name=":2">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2006/oct/27/popandrock.mychemicalromance|title=They have come for your children|work=The Guardian|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|quote="We didn't get any of the benefits of being an emo band, our influences didn't come from emo."|date=October 27, 2006|access-date=February 14, 2014|archive-date=April 9, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140409130402/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2006/oct/27/popandrock.mychemicalromance|url-status=live}}</ref> describing the genre as "fucking garbage".<ref name="nmeinterview">{{cite web| url= https://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/31256| work= NME| title= My Chemical Romance brand emo 'shit'| date= September 20, 2007| quote= "I think emo's a pile of shit ... I think emo is fucking garbage – it's bullshit."| access-date= April 21, 2020| archive-date= June 26, 2016| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160626100241/http://www.nme.com/news/my-chemical-romance/31256| url-status= live}}</ref> However, Way has reportedly also described the band's style as "What-else-ya-got-emo".<ref name="alt press" />

The band's sound usually has elements of punk rock, pop and alternative rock.<ref name=fox>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2013/03/23/my-chemical-romance-breaks-up-after-decade-plus/ |title=My Chemical Romance breaks up after decade-plus |publisher=[[Fox News]] |date=March 23, 2013 |access-date=April 4, 2013 |archive-date=April 4, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130404142212/http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2013/03/23/my-chemical-romance-breaks-up-after-decade-plus/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Way's vocals have been described as "theatrical", and espousing "introspective, confessional lyrics".<ref name="allmusic" /> The band's debut album, features a raw sound that has [[guitar riff]]s, very energetic vocals and sometimes [[Screaming (music)|screaming]]. The album has been described as emo,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/22/arts/music/22mich.html?mcubz=0 |title=Fresh From the Garden State, in Black Leather and Eyeliner |work=[[The New York Times]] |last=Michel |first=Sia |date=October 22, 2006 |access-date=July 24, 2018 |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725063353/https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/22/arts/music/22mich.html?mcubz=0 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="alternative press 22">{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/reviews/entry/ibroughtyoumybulletsyoubroughtmeyourlove|title=My Chemical Romance – I Brought You My Bullets, You Brought Me Your Love – Alternative Press|work=Alternative Press|date=June 22, 2010|access-date=April 24, 2015|archive-date=January 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160108170122/http://www.altpress.com/reviews/entry/ibroughtyoumybulletsyoubroughtmeyourlove|url-status=live}}</ref> post-hardcore,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/feb/07/popandrock.mychemicalromance |title=My Chemical Romance, Academy, London |work=[[The Guardian]] |last=Clarke |first=Betty |date=February 6, 2005 |access-date=December 15, 2016 |archive-date=January 18, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118225342/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/feb/07/popandrock.mychemicalromance |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://diffuser.fm/my-chemical-romance-worst-to-first/#photogallery-1=5 |title=Worst to First: Every My Chemical Romance Album Ranked |publisher=Diffuser |last=Manley |first=Brendan |date=February 26, 2016 |access-date=July 24, 2018 |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725033220/http://diffuser.fm/my-chemical-romance-worst-to-first/#photogallery-1=5 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Birthday>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2578314/gerard-way-birthday/ |title=Happy Birthday, Gerard Way: Wake-Up Video |publisher=[[MTV]] |last=Anderson |first=Kyle |date=April 9, 2010 |access-date=April 24, 2015 |archive-date=August 9, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809090126/http://www.mtv.com/news/2578314/gerard-way-birthday/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/an-obituary-for-my-chemical-romance |title=An Obituary For My Chemical Romance |work=[[NME]] |date=March 22, 2013 |access-date=April 24, 2015 |archive-date=March 2, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150302043129/http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/an-obituary-for-my-chemical-romance |url-status=live }}</ref> alternative rock,<ref>{{cite web|title=My Chemical Romance: I Brought You My Bullets, You Brought Me Your Love: Music|website=Amazon.com|asin=B00006EXL5|url=https://www.amazon.com/Brought-You-Bullets-Your-Love/dp/B00006EXL5|access-date=October 6, 2020|archive-date=March 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305161507/http://www.amazon.com/Brought-You-Bullets-Your-Love/dp/B00006EXL5|url-status=live}}</ref> [[screamo]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fuse.tv/2014/09/which-gerard-way-are-you-quiz |title=Which Gerard Way Are You? |publisher=[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]] |last=Sherman |first=Maria |date=September 30, 2014 |quote=<!---This quote is in one of the quiz results. --->"My Chemical Romance's first album, 'I Brought You My Bullets, You Brought Me Your Love,' was their first before reaching mega-fame. It was abrasive, dark and fully screamo". |access-date=July 24, 2018 |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725122844/https://www.fuse.tv/2014/09/which-gerard-way-are-you-quiz |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ucsdguardian.org/2006/05/11/sun-god-2006/ |title=Sun God 2006 |work=[[UCSD Guardian]] |date=May 11, 2006 |author=Edward |access-date=July 24, 2018 |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725033522/http://ucsdguardian.org/2006/05/11/sun-god-2006/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2014/06/dusting-em-off-my-chemical-romance-three-cheers-for-sweet-revenge-2/ |title=Dusting 'Em Off: My Chemical Romance - Three Cheers for Sweet Revenge |work=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=June 8, 2014 |access-date=July 24, 2018 |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725063252/https://consequenceofsound.net/2014/06/dusting-em-off-my-chemical-romance-three-cheers-for-sweet-revenge-2/ |url-status=live }}</ref> punk rock,<ref name="alternative press 22"/> gothic rock,<ref name="PopMatters"/> pop punk,<ref name="alternative press 22"/> and [[garage punk]].<ref name="Birthday" /> The album also has some influences from [[hardcore punk]] and heavy metal.<ref name="bulletsIGN">{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2004/08/04/i-brought-you-my-bullets-you-brought-me-your-love |title=I Brought You My Bullets, You Brought Me Your Love |website=IGN |date=August 14, 2004 |access-date=April 4, 2013 |archive-date=February 18, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140218205204/http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/08/04/i-brought-you-my-bullets-you-brought-me-your-love |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.altpress.com/reviews/entry/ibroughtyoumybulletsyoubroughtmeyourlove |title=My Chemical Romance – I Brought You My Bullets, You Brought Me Your Love |magazine=[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]] |date=July 23, 2002 |access-date=April 4, 2013 |archive-date=October 23, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023104023/http://www.altpress.com/reviews/entry/ibroughtyoumybulletsyoubroughtmeyourlove |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Loftus |first=Johnny |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/three-cheers-for-sweet-revenge-mw0000738265 |title=Three Cheers for Sweet Revenge – My Chemical Romance &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |website=AllMusic |date=2004-06-08 |access-date=2014-07-27 |archive-date=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303004753/https://www.allmusic.com/album/three-cheers-for-sweet-revenge-mw0000738265 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Three Cheers for Sweet Revenge'' was described as alternative rock,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guitarworld.com/my-chemical-romance-interview-and-talk-danger-days|title=My Chemical Romance interview and talk 'Danger Days'|access-date=April 26, 2015|archive-date=September 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924122355/http://www.guitarworld.com/my-chemical-romance-interview-and-talk-danger-days|url-status=live}}</ref> emo,<ref name="spin 33">{{cite magazine |date=March 26, 2013 |title=Three Cheers for Sweet Career: Farewell, My Chemical Romance |url=https://www.spin.com/2005/05/my-chemical-romance/-mcr-breakup-best-songs-in-memoriam |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |access-date=April 4, 2013}}</ref> pop punk,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/7348/My-Chemical-Romance-Three-Cheers-for-Sweet-Revenge/|title=My Chemical Romance – Three Cheers for Sweet Revenge (album review 8) – Sputnikmusic|access-date=April 24, 2015|archive-date=April 24, 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150424131738/http://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/7348/My-Chemical-Romance-Three-Cheers-for-Sweet-Revenge/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/my-chemical-romance/11724|title=NME Reviews - Album Review: My Chemical Romance - Danger Days: The True Lives Of The Fabulous Killjoys (Warner) - NME.COM|date=November 19, 2010|work=NME|access-date=April 24, 2015|archive-date=May 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526014300/http://www.nme.com/reviews/my-chemical-romance/11724|url-status=live}}</ref> post-hardcore,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/books-comics/5735/the-umbrella-academy-1-review|title=The Umbrella Academy #1 review|work=Den of Geek|date=October 10, 2007|access-date=April 26, 2015|archive-date=July 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713030541/http://www.denofgeek.us/books-comics/5735/the-umbrella-academy-1-review|url-status=live}}</ref> and punk rock.<ref>{{cite news |title='Three Cheers' for Romance |work=[[The Free Lance–Star]] |last=Briganti |first=Skyler |page=26 |date=August 26, 2004}}</ref> The band's third album, ''The Black Parade,'' has been described as alternative rock,<ref name="The Black Parade AllMusic">{{cite web |url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r929929/review|pure_url=yes}} |title=''The Black Parade'' – My Chemical Romance |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=July 2, 2008 |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |author-link=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dSEI4YsawBwC&q=%22The+Black+Parade%22+%22alt+rock%22&pg=PA193|title=Frontman: Surviving the Rock Star Myth|isbn=9780879309121|access-date=April 24, 2015|last1=Barone|first1=Richard|year=2007|archive-date=October 21, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211021171706/https://books.google.com/books?id=dSEI4YsawBwC&q=%22The+Black+Parade%22+%22alt+rock%22&pg=PA193|url-status=live}}</ref> emo,<ref name="The Black Parade AllMusic" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/review/my-chemical-romance-the-black-parade/|title=My Chemical Romance|work=PopMatters|date=November 8, 2006|access-date=April 24, 2015|archive-date=July 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724005433/http://www.popmatters.com/review/my-chemical-romance-the-black-parade/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/2011-05-19/music/my-chemical-romance-shed-their-emo-roots/full/|title=My Chemical Romance Shed Their Emo Roots|last=Smyers|first=Darryl|date=May 18, 2011|access-date=April 24, 2015|archive-date=May 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518021914/http://www.dallasobserver.com/2011-05-19/music/my-chemical-romance-shed-their-emo-roots/full|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/226023/get-ready-to-be-miserable-again-the-emo-sommelier-is-back|title=Get Ready To Be Miserable Again: The Emo Sommelier Is Back!|work=Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on Idolator.com|access-date=April 24, 2015|archive-date=April 24, 2015|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150424030753/http://www.idolator.com/226023/get-ready-to-be-miserable-again-the-emo-sommelier-is-back|url-status=live}}</ref> pop punk,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/9678/My-Chemical-Romance-The-Black-Parade/|title=My Chemical Romance – The Black Parade (album review 18) – Sputnikmusic|access-date=April 24, 2015|archive-date=January 4, 2013|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130104203814/http://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/9678/My-Chemical-Romance-The-Black-Parade/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1153104701.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924202541/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1153104701.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 24, 2015|title=MY CHEMICAL ROMANCE / The Black Parade (Reprise/Warner)|access-date=April 24, 2015}}</ref> post-hardcore,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaquarian.com/2006/11/08/my-chemical-romance-interview-with-frank-iero/|title=My Chemical Romance: Interview with Frank Iero|work=The Aquarian Weekly|access-date=April 24, 2015|archive-date=July 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721231812/http://www.theaquarian.com/2006/11/08/my-chemical-romance-interview-with-frank-iero/|url-status=live}}</ref> punk rock,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ryan|first1=Kyle|title=My Chemical Romance: The Black Parade|url=https://www.avclub.com/review/my-chemical-romance-emthe-black-paradeem-8103|website=A.V. Club|date=October 31, 2006 |access-date=April 21, 2020|archive-date=August 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819060626/http://www.avclub.com/review/my-chemical-romance-emthe-black-paradeem-8103|url-status=live}}</ref> and hard rock.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=6592646|title=The Black Parade|publisher=NPR Music|date=December 7, 2006|access-date=September 22, 2018|archive-date=September 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923010024/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=6592646|url-status=live}}</ref> The album has influences from 1970s classic rock,<ref name="altpress">{{cite journal |url=http://www.altpress.com/reviews/entry/theblackparade/ |title=My Chemical Romance: ''The Black Parade'' |journal=[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]] |date=October 23, 2006 |access-date=January 17, 2011 |last=Pettigrew |first=Jason |archive-date=November 3, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101103093246/http://www.altpress.com/reviews/entry/theblackparade/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="patrick">{{cite web |url=http://blogcritics.org/music/article/music-review-my-chemical-romance-the1/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511113918/http://blogcritics.org/music/article/music-review-my-chemical-romance-the1/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 11, 2009 |title=Music Review: My Chemical Romance – The Black Parade |publisher=Patrick Meany |date=March 24, 2013 |access-date=April 5, 2013 }}</ref><ref name="IGN">{{cite web | first=Ed | last=Thompson | title=My Chemical Romance – The Black Parade | website=IGN | url=http://music.ign.com/articles/741/741718p1.html | access-date=2008-07-01 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101216045855/http://music.ign.com/articles/741/741718p1.html | archive-date=2010-12-16 }}</ref> glam rock,<ref name="altpress" /><ref name="spinreview">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/my-chemical-romance-black-parade-reprise |title=My Chemical Romance, 'The Black Parade' |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|SPIN]] |date=October 24, 2006 |access-date=April 5, 2013 |archive-date=April 1, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130401075203/http://www.spin.com/reviews/my-chemical-romance-black-parade-reprise |url-status=live }}</ref> pop,<ref name="about">{{cite web |url=http://top40.about.com/od/albums/fr/blackparade.htm |title=My Chemical Romance – The Black Parade |publisher=Bill Lamb |access-date=April 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616182907/http://top40.about.com/od/albums/fr/blackparade.htm |archive-date=June 16, 2013 }}</ref> and gothic rock.<ref name="spinreview" /> The band's fourth album, ''Danger Days: The True Lives of the Fabulous Killjoys,'' integrated elements of [[power pop]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2010-12-01/music/my-chemical-romance-go-styx/|title=My Chemical Romance Go ... Styx|author=Christopher R. Weingarten|date=November 30, 2010|access-date=April 24, 2015|quote=But unlike that album's garish guyliner anthems about death and disease, their new Danger Days: The True Lives of the Fabulous Killjoys is a 15-track power-pop cycle that's a lot less Queen and a lot more Styx ...|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110416103927/http://www.villagevoice.com/2010-12-01/music/my-chemical-romance-go-styx/|archive-date=April 16, 2011}}</ref> [[pop rock]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/review/134152-my-chemical-romance-danger-days-the-true-lives-of-the-fabulous-killj/|title=My Chemical Romance|work=PopMatters|date=November 30, 2010|access-date=April 24, 2015|quote=With that said, though, Danger Days is a far cry from the artistic plane that The Black Parade sits on: it's a decent pop-rock album, a disastrously confused concept album, and even with its marketing, much is left to be desired.|archive-date=August 2, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802054922/http://www.popmatters.com/review/134152-my-chemical-romance-danger-days-the-true-lives-of-the-fabulous-killj/|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[electronic rock]] into their sound.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rollingstoneindia.com/my-chemical-romance/|title=My Chemical Romance|work=Rolling Stone India|date=December 20, 2010|access-date=April 26, 2015|quote=Leaving theatrical gloom behind, the Jersey boys make a blazing synth-rock album|archive-date=March 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330195516/http://rollingstoneindia.com/my-chemical-romance/|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[Gerard Way]] said to ''Rolling Stone'', "we love bands like [[Queen (band)|Queen]], where it's huge and majestic, but also bands like [[Black Flag (band)|Black Flag]] and the [[Misfits (band)|Misfits]], who would go absolutely crazy."<ref>{{cite book |last1=La Bella |first1=Laura |title=My Chemical Romance |date=2008 |publisher=he Rosen Publishing Group, Inc |page=24}}</ref> Way has stated that the band is heavily influenced by Queen, Misfits, Black Flag, [[Iron Maiden]], [[the Cure]], [[Joy Division]], [[Bauhaus (band)|Bauhaus]], [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[the Smiths]] and [[Morrissey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/videos/shows/subterranean/108030/gerard-way-tells-about-my-chemical-romances-influences.jhtml |title=Gerard Way tells about My Chemical Romance's influences &#124; Video |publisher=MTV |date=2006-09-14 |access-date=2011-05-14 |archive-date=December 13, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213074919/http://www.mtv.com/videos/shows/subterranean/108030/gerard-way-tells-about-my-chemical-romances-influences.jhtml |url-status=live }}</ref> Way has also said that his band patterns their career after that of [[the Smashing Pumpkins]], another band they admire.<ref>{{cite web | author= Tyme, Gwyn | date=2005-05-05| title=My Chemical Romance—Interview with Gerard Way | publisher= MusicPix.net | url= http://www.musicpix.net/home/content/my-chemical-romance-interview-gerard-way-live-photos | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100612033439/http://www.musicpix.net/home/content/my-chemical-romance-interview-gerard-way-live-photos | archive-date= June 12, 2010 | access-date= 2006-11-05}} Retrieved from Internet Archive February 16, 2014.</ref> Frank Iero cites the punk band [[Lifetime (band)|Lifetime]] as a big influence.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2006/03/lifetime-rock/ |title=A Lifetime of Rock |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=March 24, 2006 |access-date=November 11, 2018 |archive-date=August 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811032804/https://www.spin.com/2006/03/lifetime-rock/ |url-status=live }}</ref> My Chemical Romance's other influences include [[the Stooges]], [[Ramones]], [[Sex Pistols]], [[the Clash]], [[Minor Threat]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], and [[Operation Ivy (band)|Operation Ivy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/my-chemical-romances-frank-iero-the-10-greatest-punk-albums-of-all-time-514878 |title=My Chemical Romance's Frank Iero: the 10 greatest punk albums of all time |publisher=MusicRadar |last=Bosso |first=Joe |date=November 22, 2011 |access-date=February 28, 2019 |archive-date=March 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301140318/https://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/my-chemical-romances-frank-iero-the-10-greatest-punk-albums-of-all-time-514878 |url-status=live }}</ref> They also have noted that their lives, childhoods, books they've read and movies they've seen have influenced their music.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M3NTg2bfVrM|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201005130329/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M3NTg2bfVrM&app=desktop|archive-date=October 5, 2020|title=Live streamed chat w/ My Chemical Romance|website=[[YouTube]]|access-date=December 2, 2020|time=3:20|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Legacy==

=== Music and popular culture ===
According to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', the band played "somewhat of an anomaly in New Jersey's then-burgeoning pop-punk and emo scene", before achieving their breakthrough with an "instant emo classic" ''Three Cheers for Sweet Revenge,''<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Suzy|last=Exposito|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-live-reviews/my-chemical-romance-reunion-show-los-angeles-928097/|title=My Chemical Romance Marches On Again at Los Angeles Reunion Show|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=December 21, 2019|access-date=March 17, 2022|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20201128024949/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-live-reviews/my-chemical-romance-reunion-show-los-angeles-928097/|archivedate=November 28, 2020}}</ref> while [[Spin (magazine)|''Spin'']] described it as one of the albums that launched the emo genre into the mainstream.<ref name="spin 33" /> In 2022, ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that during the height of their career they were "unlikely superstars, misfits who inadvertently infiltrated the mainstream" but upon their reunion tour, the band "return to a pop cultural landscape they helped to define".<ref name=":1" /> ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}}s Christopher R. Weingarten has noted that ''The Black Parade'' inspired a number of 2010s musicians in different genres, including [[Twenty One Pilots]], [[Crown the Empire]], [[Famous Last Words (band)|Famous Last Words]], [[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]], [[Fun (band)|fun]], [[Billie Eilish]] and [[Post Malone]], and even influenced the sound of [[movie musical]]s like ''[[Frozen II]]''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Christopher R.|last=Weingarten|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/12/18/arts/music/my-chemical-romance-black-parade.html|title=Before & After 'The Black Parade'|website=The New York Times|date=December 18, 2019|access-date=March 17, 2022|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20210308064954/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/12/18/arts/music/my-chemical-romance-black-parade.html|archivedate=March 8, 2021}}</ref> In 2016, ''[[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]]'' wrote that the record "took the idea of a [[concept album]] and exploited it for the [[Information Age|digital age]]", while being musically a [[rock opera]] "as ambitious as any post-[[Queen (band)|Queen]] rock opera could be".<ref>{{cite web|first=Hayden|last=Manders|url=https://www.nylon.com/articles/my-chemical-romance-the-black-parade-10th-anniversary|title=The Enduring Legacy Of My Chemical Romance's 'The Black Parade'|website=Nylon|date=October 23, 2016|access-date=March 17, 2022|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20210201083929/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/12/18/arts/music/my-chemical-romance-black-parade.html|archivedate=February 1, 2021}}</ref> Speaking on the band's reception and criticism during the early 2000s, [[NPR Music]] wrote that, "at a moment when mannered indie-pop and roughshod garage-rock were infiltrating the mainstream, [the band] was earnest, dramatic and unapologetically massive, in a way that made it conspicuously uncool," and deemed ''The Black Parade'' a "defining album" for a generation of pop-punk fans.<ref>{{cite web|first=Daoud|last=Tyler-Ameen|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2016/10/21/498852294/join-the-black-parade-my-chemical-romance-and-the-politics-of-taste|title=Join The Black Parade: My Chemical Romance And The Politics Of Taste|website=NPR Music|date=October 21, 2016|access-date=March 17, 2022|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200831114930/https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2016/10/21/498852294/join-the-black-parade-my-chemical-romance-and-the-politics-of-taste|archivedate=August 31, 2020}}</ref>

In 2020, ''[[Kerrang!]]'' deemed the band "the rock superstars of the 21st century" while stating that "no other band has had such a musical or cultural impact over recent years."<ref>{{cite web|first=Paul|last=Travers|url=https://www.kerrang.com/10-moments-that-made-my-chemical-romance-superstars?next=|title=10 Moments That Made My Chemical Romance Superstars|website=Kerrang!|date=November 27, 2020|access-date=March 17, 2022}}</ref> The magazine also noted their influence in "the current music scene" of [[alternative rock]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Paul|last=Travers|url=https://www.kerrang.com/12-bands-who-wouldnt-have-been-possible-without-my-chemical-romance|title=12 bands who wouldn't be here without My Chemical Romance|website=Kerrang!|date=March 4, 2021|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20211220115231/https://www.kerrang.com/12-bands-who-wouldnt-have-been-possible-without-my-chemical-romance|archivedate=December 20, 2021}}</ref> ''[[Vice (website)|Vice]]'' named My Chemical Romance the "artist of the decade", with writer Hannah Ewens commenting that they "influenced rock throughout the 2010s—even though they were inactive for most of the decade."<ref>{{cite web|first=Hannah|last=Ewens|url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/8xwjj5/my-chemical-romance-is-the-artist-of-the-decade|title=My Chemical Romance Is the Artist of the Decade|website=Vice|date=November 13, 2019|access-date=March 17, 2022|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20201003212708/https://www.vice.com/en/article/8xwjj5/my-chemical-romance-is-the-artist-of-the-decade|archivedate=October 3, 2020}}</ref> In [[Paste (magazine)|''Paste'' magazine]], Eli Enis wrote that "it is pretty much accepted canon at this point that My Chemical Romance are one of the most significant rock bands this side of the millennium."<ref>{{cite web|first=Eli|last=Enis|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/my-chemical-romance/my-chemical-romance-underrated-songs/|title=The 10 Most Underrated My Chemical Romance Songs|website=Paste|date=January 21, 2020|access-date=March 17, 2022}}</ref> James McMahon of ''[[The Independent]]'' stated that Gerard Way "set a blueprint for emo's image of pale face, raven-black hair and perhaps a red tie, for almost 20 years."<ref name=":6">{{cite web|first=James|last=McMahon|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/emo-music-my-chemical-romance-paramore-hayley-williams-green-day-a9412056.html|title=Miserable at best: How emo bounced back from the brink|website=The Independent|date=October 23, 2020|access-date=March 17, 2022|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20201123172818/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/emo-music-my-chemical-romance-paramore-hayley-williams-green-day-a9412056.html|archivedate=November 23, 2020}}</ref> Writing on the band's influence, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s Kyle Anderson stated that they "offered up spiritual solutions to real problems, and they did it with huge riffs and big theatrical stage shows, with rarely a hint of irony or detachment... it's unlikely there will ever be a band quite like them again."<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Kyle|last=Anderson|url=https://ew.com/article/2013/03/25/my-chemical-romance-break-up/|title=My Chemical Romance: The last most important band on the planet|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|date=March 25, 2013|access-date=March 17, 2022|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20211023142810/https://ew.com/article/2013/03/25/my-chemical-romance-break-up/|archivedate=October 23, 2021}}</ref>

=== LGBT community ===
In [[Archer (magazine)|''Archer'']], Vince Ruston commented on the band's popularity in the [[queer]] and [[LGBT community|LGBT communities]]: "My Chemical Romance wanted to speak to and raise up every person who had ever felt outcast, downtrodden, or [[Social alienation|alienated]]. Queer teens were a huge part of that demographic".<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |date=2021-12-09 |title=My Chemical Romance: On queer emo friendship |url=https://archermagazine.com.au/2021/12/queer-emo-friendship-my-chemical-romance/ |access-date=2022-05-22 |website=Archer Magazine |language=en-US}}</ref> Similarly, Michelle Hyun Kim described Gerard Way as a "[[queer icon]]" in [[Them (website)|''Them'']], and that "after the band announced their reunion on Halloween 2019, I saw tweets from LGBTQ+ folks around the world claiming, in some way or another, that MCR either served as a queer awakening or fostered their queerness."<ref>{{Cite web |date=2020-03-19 |title=How My Chemical Romance's Gerard Way Became a Queer Icon |url=https://www.them.us/story/my-chemical-romance-gerard-way-queer-fandom |access-date=2022-05-22 |website=them. |language=en-US}}</ref> The band have long been supportive of [[LGBT rights by country or territory|LGBT rights]]<ref name=":4" /> and embraced their LGBT fandom.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-05-17 |title=Yes, My Chemical Romance Is Really Selling a Gay Tramp Stamp Shirt |url=https://www.them.us/story/my-chemical-romance-merch-tramp-stamp-shirt |access-date=2022-05-23 |website=them. |language=en-US}}</ref>

==Tours==
[[File:Mikey Way performing.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|left|Bassist Mikey Way, dressed in his Black Parade uniform]]

===2000s===
My Chemical Romance played in many major tours of 2005. The band toured with Green Day in 2005 on the "[[American Idiot World Tour|Green Day Presents American Idiot Tour]]". They were also part of the [[Warped Tour]] in the same year. "For a lot of kids, it's the one thing they look forward to all year," said Gerard Way of the Warped Tour. "They save up for it. They get to see all the bands they like in one shot."<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Brian Hiatt, Posted June 22, 2005 12:00 AM |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/mychemicalromance/articles/story/7415954/warped_tour_conquers_us |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070604174246/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/mychemicalromance/articles/story/7415954/warped_tour_conquers_us |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 4, 2007 |title=Warped Tour Conquers U.S.: My Chemical Romance |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=2005-06-22 |access-date=2010-03-13}}</ref> Their set list included mostly songs from ''Three Cheers for Sweet Revenge''.

My Chemical Romance co-headlined the main stage with The Used on the Taste of Chaos tour, before starting their first headlining tour, simply named the "My Chemical Romance Tour".  The tour launched September 15 in Ohio, stopping at 30 locations in the United States, to promote their album, ''Three Cheers for Sweet Revenge''. Supporting acts included [[Alkaline Trio]] and [[Reggie and the Full Effect]]. This tour marked the beginning of the heavy theatrics later showcased in many of their live shows. Way expressed his plans for the tour in an interview with MTV, saying, "we'd talked about bringing out dancers for our headlining tour in the fall, but it's a big undertaking; you have to have a bus full of dancers. We've always wanted to do a big theatrical tour. But you have to do it in steps".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1506771/20050801/my_chemical_romance.jhtml |title=My Chemical Romance Fall Tour : Arena Rock On The Installment Plan |last=Montgomery |first=James |publisher=Mtv.com |access-date=2014-07-27 |archive-date=September 13, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070913093422/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1506771/20050801/my_chemical_romance.jhtml |url-status=live }}</ref>

The band joined headliners [[Linkin Park]] on [[Projekt Revolution]] 2007, starting on July 25 and ending on September 3, 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkinpark.com/home|title=Chester Performs with Julien-K|date=August 30, 2007|website=Linkin Park|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070913002752/http://linkinpark.com/projektrevolution/member/projektrevolution|archive-date=September 13, 2007}}</ref> The band played a one-hour set on center stage, opening with "This Is How I Disappear", as flames burst behind the band. The set ended with "Cancer", occasionally accompanied by falling confetti, and fireworks.  Following the Projekt Revolution tour, they opened for [[Bon Jovi]] in October and then departed for a European Tour with [[Mindless Self Indulgence]].

===2010s===
{{Main|The World Contamination Tour|10th Annual Honda Civic Tour}}
{{expand section|date=June 2020}}
On September 19, 2010, the band announced "The World Contamination Tour", which took place in parts of the UK, France, Amsterdam and Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/siteadmin/%E2%80%9Cworld-contamination-tour%E2%80%9D-tickets-sale|title=World Contamination Tour announced|publisher=Mychemicalromance.com|access-date=2014-07-27|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321102126/http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/siteadmin/%E2%80%9Cworld-contamination-tour%E2%80%9D-tickets-sale|archive-date=2012-03-21}}</ref>

The band embarked on [[10th Annual Honda Civic Tour|a joint tour]] of the United States with [[Blink-182]] in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2011-05-24 |title=Blink-182 to Tour with My Chemical Romance |url=https://www.spin.com/2011/05/blink-182s-delonge-tour-my-chem/ |access-date=2022-05-23 |website=SPIN |language=en-US}}</ref>

The band reunited out of the public eye in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MCRofficial/status/1207909921930371072|title=In 2017, we got in a room together to see what would happen. A couple more jam sessions and 39 days of rehearsals later, we're ready to show you what we've learned. See you soon.pic.twitter.com/1c4FJrTI45|author=My Chemical Romance|date=2019-12-19|website=@MCRofficial|language=en|access-date=2019-12-22|archive-date=November 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201111234423/https://twitter.com/MCRofficial/status/1207909921930371072?s=19|url-status=live}}</ref> and announced a reunion show on October 31, 2019, which took place in [[Los Angeles]] on December 20, 2019, extending this to a small tour consisting of dates in Australia, New Zealand and Japan a week later.<ref name="pitchfork.com"/><ref name="Campbell"/>

===2020s===
{{Main|My Chemical Romance Reunion Tour}}
On January 28, 2020, the group announced plans to present three concerts in [[Milton Keynes]] (UK), on 18, 20 and 21 of June 2020.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/my-chemical-romance-2020-uk-tour-dates-tickets-milton-keynes-a4338766.html | title= My Chemical Romance 2020 UK tour: Milton Keynes dates, ticket information and venues | newspaper= [[Evening Standard]] | author= Tom Herbert, Emma Clarke | date= January 28, 2020 | access-date= January 28, 2020 | archive-date= January 28, 2020 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200128110628/https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/my-chemical-romance-2020-uk-tour-dates-tickets-milton-keynes-a4338766.html | url-status= live }}</ref> On January 29, 2020, the band announced a North American tour.<ref name=asummoning>{{Citation|title=A summoning...|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=15-wGHtIOeo|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130061215/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=15-wGHtIOeo|archive-date=January 30, 2020|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/my-chemical-romance-announce-full-reunion-tour/|title=My Chemical Romance Announce Full Reunion Tour|website=Pitchfork|date=January 29, 2020|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29|archive-date=January 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129201958/https://pitchfork.com/news/my-chemical-romance-announce-full-reunion-tour/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In April 2020, during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], the group postponed its Milton Keynes events, initially to June 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |title=My Chemical Romance's Milton Keynes reunion concerts postponed until 2021 |url=https://www.miltonkeynes.co.uk/health/coronavirus/my-chemical-romances-milton-keynes-reunion-concerts-postponed-until-2021-2551826 |access-date=2021-02-01 |work=Milton Keynes Citizen |date=April 27, 2020 |language=en |archive-date=May 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200502223629/https://www.miltonkeynes.co.uk/health/coronavirus/my-chemical-romances-milton-keynes-reunion-concerts-postponed-until-2021-2551826 |url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2020, the band postponed all North American events to September and October 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|title=My Chemical Romance {{!}} Official Website|url=https://www.mychemicalromance.com/|access-date=2021-02-01|website=My Chemical Romance Official Website|language=en|archive-date=March 25, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325024121/http://www.mychemicalromance.com/blog/mcr/my-chemical-romance|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2021, the Milton Keynes concert was postponed again to May 2022.<ref>{{cite news | title=My Chemical Romance postpone Milton Keynes gigs until 2022 | url=https://www.miltonkeynes.co.uk/whats-on/arts-and-entertainment/my-chemical-romance-postpone-milton-keynes-gigs-until-2022-3204201 | author=David Jackson | date=16 April 2021 | work=Milton Keynes Citizen | access-date=April 17, 2021 | archive-date=April 17, 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210417214327/https://www.miltonkeynes.co.uk/whats-on/arts-and-entertainment/my-chemical-romance-postpone-milton-keynes-gigs-until-2022-3204201 | url-status=live }}</ref> The rest of the tour was later postponed to 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Campbell|first=Rachel|date=2021-04-16|title=My Chemical Romance reschedule tour dates for 2022|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/my-chemical-romance-rescheduled-tour-dates-2022/|access-date=2021-06-11|website=Alternative Press|language=en-US|archive-date=June 11, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210611134014/https://www.altpress.com/news/my-chemical-romance-rescheduled-tour-dates-2022/|url-status=live}}</ref>

